================================================================================
7. KEY INSIGHTS
================================================================================

7.1 RAG's Advantage: Semantic Disambiguation
  The embedding captures not just the symbol name but the surrounding
  code context. When searching for "NamespaceService.deleteNamespace",
  the embedding of the query is closer to the portal module version
  (which deals with namespace deletion logic) than the biz module
  version. This gives RAG a structural advantage that grep (pure text
  matching) cannot achieve.

7.2 Grep's Advantage: Precision on Unique Names
  When a symbol name is globally unique (e.g., "ApolloEurekaClientConfig"),
  grep finds it in one step with zero ambiguity. RAG's semantic search
  can return similar-but-wrong results, leading to occasional wrong_line
  errors on tasks that Grep solves trivially.

7.3 The Shared Bottleneck: Method Overloads
  Both agents fail on overloaded methods within the same class
  (e.g., NamespaceService.isChildNamespace at line 280 vs 284).
  This is a fundamental limitation of the current 4-step constraint
  — resolving overloads requires reading and understanding method
  signatures, which consumes steps.

7.4 Infrastructure Quality Matters
  Grep had 4 API errors (8% of tasks) while RAG had 0. This may be
  because RAG's vector search provides better first-pass context,
  reducing the number of LLM round trips and thus API error exposure.
  However, this could also be random variation in a single run.

7.5 Difficulty Anomaly Explained
  In the Grep-only experiment, hard tasks (50%) outperformed medium
  tasks (33.3%). With RAG, this anomaly disappears:
  - Medium jumps from 33.3% → 80.0% (RAG fixes ambiguous names)
  - Hard stays at 50% (overload disambiguation remains unsolved)
  This confirms that medium tasks were the Grep-specific weakness,
  not an inherent difficulty ordering.

================================================================================
8. CONCLUSION
================================================================================

RAG outperforms Grep by 10 percentage points (78% vs 68%) on the Apollo
codebase symbol localization benchmark. The advantage is concentrated on
method search (+39.1%) where semantic disambiguation resolves the
ambiguous-name problem that plagues text-based grep.

However, Grep remains superior on unique-name symbols (class/enum/
interface) where exact text matching is faster and more precise.

The ideal agent would combine both approaches:
  1. Try grep first for exact-name matches (fast, precise)
  2. Fall back to vector search when grep returns too many hits
    (semantic disambiguation)

This hybrid approach could potentially achieve >85% success rate and
represents the natural next step for this research.

================================================================================
9. EXPERIMENT SCOPE AND LIMITATIONS
================================================================================

This experiment was originally motivated by the question: "Why does Claude
Code use Grep rather than RAG for code search?" The results show RAG
outperforming Grep on our benchmark. This section clarifies what the
experiment actually measured, what it did not measure, and what the
results mean in the broader context of code search tool design.

9.1 What We Tested
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  - Task: Symbol definition localization (find the exact file:line of a
    class/method/enum/interface definition)
  - Codebase: Fixed snapshot of Apollo (510 Java files, 7 modules)
  - Condition: Pre-built vector index, no code changes during evaluation
  - Metric: Precision (file + line ±3)
  - Constraint: 4-step budget per task

  Under these specific conditions, RAG achieved 78% vs Grep's 68%.

9.2 What We Did NOT Test
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  The following dimensions were not part of this experiment but are
  critical to understanding why production tools like Claude Code prefer
  Grep:

  a) Index Build Cost
     Building the RAG index required:
     - 3916 embedding API calls (DashScope text-embedding-v4)
     - ~5 minutes of wall-clock time
     - Monetary cost for embedding API usage
     Grep requires zero setup — ripgrep is a single binary.

  b) Index Freshness / Code Mutation
     Real codebases change constantly. After a file is modified:
     - Grep sees the change immediately
     - RAG's index is stale until rebuilt (partial or full)
     In a rapidly-changing codebase, RAG's accuracy degrades unless
     the index is continuously updated — adding ongoing cost and
     complexity.

  c) General Search Scenarios
     Our benchmark only tests symbol definition localization. Real
     code search includes:
     - Exact text search (error codes, TODO comments, variable names)
     - Call-site discovery ("who calls this method?")
     - Pattern matching ("all uses of deprecated API X")
     - Cross-file refactoring searches
     Grep excels at all of these. RAG's semantic similarity may not
     be the right tool for exact/pattern-based searches.

  d) Codebase Scale
     Apollo has 510 Java files. Production codebases have tens of
     thousands. At that scale:
     - Index build time/cost grows linearly
     - Vector search latency may increase
     - Index maintenance becomes a non-trivial engineering problem
     Grep scales naturally — ripgrep is designed for millions of files.

  e) End-to-End Task Completion
     We measured search precision, not whether the agent ultimately
     answered the user's question correctly. In Claude Code's
     architecture, search is just the first step — the LLM then reads
     and reasons about the code. A slightly less precise search tool
     may still lead to correct answers if the LLM can self-correct.

9.3 What This Means
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  The experiment answers a specific question:

    "For symbol definition localization on a fixed, small codebase with
     pre-built index, which retrieval method is more accurate?"

    Answer: RAG (78% vs 68%).

  It does NOT answer:

    "Which retrieval method is better for a production code search tool?"

  The reason Claude Code uses Grep is likely not about raw search
  accuracy on a narrow benchmark. It is about the total engineering
  tradeoff:

    Grep advantages (not measured here):
    ✓ Zero infrastructure — no index, no embedding model, no vector DB
    ✓ Always fresh — sees code changes instantly
    ✓ General purpose — handles exact text, patterns, regex, not just
      symbol definitions
    ✓ Predictable cost — single binary, no API calls, no tokens
    ✓ Scales trivially — ripgrep handles millions of files

    RAG advantages (measured here):
    ✓ Better at disambiguating ambiguous symbol names (+39% on methods)
    ✓ Semantic understanding — finds related code, not just exact matches
    ✓ Cross-language potential — embeddings can bridge naming conventions

  The honest conclusion is: RAG is more accurate for this specific task,
  but Grep's engineering advantages (zero cost, real-time freshness,
  generality) make it the pragmatic choice for a general-purpose code
  search tool. The two are not in direct competition — they solve
  different problems.

